        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/HLTev.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 3557625,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2970947,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2970947/elliott-frisch",
                "reputation": 201916,
                "display_name": "Elliott Frisch"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 5,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1415032369,
            "creation_date": 1415032369,
            "body": "<p>The semicolon terminates your loop body; and then you have an anonymous block. Remove the semicolon. And your test should be something like,<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>for (int index=0; index &lt; allowed.length; index++) // ;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Unless you need <code>index<\/code> again later. Additionally, you can also print an array without a loop using <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/Arrays.html#toString%28java.lang.Object[]%29\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>Arrays.toString(Object[])<\/code><\/a> and something like<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>System.out.println(Arrays.toString(allowed));\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 26718621,
            "question_id": 26718580
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/BUmKz.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 4878731,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 3933089,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3933089/chiastic-security",
                "reputation": 20540,
                "display_name": "chiastic-security",
                "accept_rate": 67
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1415034532,
            "creation_date": 1415034532,
            "body": "<p>Others have answered what you did wrong. You also asked what you're missing, so let me add something there too.<\/p>\n\n<p>You intended for <code>index<\/code> to be a variable that should be used inside your loop and nowhere else. The right way to make sure it was in scope in the loop and not elsewhere was this:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>for(int index=0; index &lt; allowed.length - 1; index++) {\n  //...\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>and then drop the declaration of <code>index<\/code> in the line above. If you had done this, then you would have discovered the semicolon typo: the compiler would have told you that <code>index<\/code> was not in scope in the <code>println()<\/code> call.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 26719252,
            "question_id": 26718580
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/jXcg4.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 1263831,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1221571,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1221571/eran",
                "reputation": 395099,
                "display_name": "Eran",
                "accept_rate": 67
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1415032257,
            "creation_date": 1415032257,
            "body": "<p>Remove the extra <code>;<\/code><\/p>\n\n<pre><code>for(index=0; index &lt; allowed.length - 1; index++)\n                                                 ^\n                                                 |\n                                                 removed `;`\n{\n  System.out.println(allowed[index]);\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Otherwise, your loop would have an empty body.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 26718587,
            "question_id": 26718580
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/TgXEW.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 794766,
